{{Globalize|date=April 2018}} This is a '''list of women [[Military history|military historians]]'''. Traditionally an overwhelmingly male-dominated discipline,<ref> {{Cite journal |last=Lynn |first=John A. |author-link=John A. Lynn |year=1997 |title=The embattled future of academic military history |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/195642876 |url-access=subscription |journal=The Journal of Military History |volume=61 |pages=777–789 |jstor=2954086 |quote=Moreover, military history is a remarkably male field, both in that we study institutions that have been overwhelmingly male and in that women are underrepresented among military historians as a group. The uncharitable might claim that as opposed to women's history, military history is men's history par excellence. |via=ProQuest}}</ref> women began entering the field with the turn towards the 'new military history' of the 1960s. Pioneering women military historians included [[Joanna Bourke]] and [[Amanda Foreman (historian)|Amanda Foreman]], who contributed to re-orientating military history towards a "multidisciplinary approach that embeds war in its political, social, cultural and personal contexts".<ref> {{Cite news |last=Lovell |first=Julia |date=2011-09-30 |title=Military history: not just for men |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/sep/30/julia-lovel-author-author |work=The Guardian |accessdate=2017-10-12 }}</ref> However, women remain under-represented in academic military history.<ref> {{Cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.nam.ac.uk/whats-on/5x15-talks-women-military-history |title=5x15 talks: Women in military history |publisher=[[National Army Museum]] |access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref>
