'''Stan Steiner''' (1925–1987) was an [[United States|American]] [[historian]] and [[teacher]] who authored works generally focusing on American [[Minority group|minority communities]] and their relationship to the broader [[Society of the United States|U.S. society]] as well as the [[mythology]] of the [[American frontier]]. Born in the [[Coney Island]] area of [[New York, New York]], he wrote a number of books touching upon various subjects from the 1960s to 1980s. He expressed particular interest in [[Native Americans in the United States|indigenous American peoples]] and their [[History of Native Americans in the United States|complex history]] into the 20th century. As an instructor, he lectured at a variety of U.S. institutions, including the [[University of New Mexico]].<ref name="Dead"/><ref name="Vanishing"/>

==Life and career==
Although his writings became strongly associated with the American heartland, Steiner was born in the [[Coney Island]] area of [[New York, New York]]. After moving around in his early years, he underwent studies at the [[University of Wisconsin]].<ref name="Dead"/> His parents had [[Immigration to the United States|immigrated to the U.S.]] from the nation of [[Austria]].

Specific works by Steiner include ''The New Indians'' (1968), ''La Raza: The Mexican Americans'' (1970), ''The Vanishing White Man'' (1976), and ''The Ranchers: A Book of Generations'' (1980). As a professor, he notably taught at the [[University of New Mexico]]. He lectured at various other U.S. institutions as well.<ref name="Dead">{{citenews|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/15/obituaries/stan-steiner-is-dead-at-62-author-consultant-teacher.html|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|title=Stan Steiner Is Dead at 62; Author, Consultant, Teacher|accessdate=May 25, 2018}}</ref>

A 1976 article on his then latest book by ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' remarked that it was "to Steiner's credit that he includes the testimony of other Western voices" regular readers studying the [[American frontier|U.S. frontier]] don't often hear, including "a Hopi elder, a thoughtful young Indian activist, a white Montana rancher, Senator Abourezk of South Dakota, Black Elk's granddaughter, and others." The analysis of ''The Vanishing White Man'', looking into the [[Culture|cultural contrast]] argument about modern U.S. citizens breaking the 'circle of life' cycle and connection to the land held by prior generations of [[Native Americans in the United States|indigenous American peoples]], followed-up from similar observations made in his 1968 book that he titled ''The New Indians''.<ref name="Vanishing">{{cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/stan-steiner/the-vanishing-white-man/|title=The Vanishing White Man - By Stan Steiner|website=[[Kirkus Reviews]]|accessdate=May 25, 2018}}</ref>

The same publication praised his later work ''The Ranchers: A Book of Generations''. In it, Steiner detailed the lives of a group of ranchers living in traditional fashion within several rural areas, the author going into the [[Individualism|individualist approaches]] aiming at maintaining self-sufficiency that the men and women had struggled with. Finding the "not sentimental" work still "sometimes moving", ''Kirkus Reviews'' declared, "As a composite picture of the vanishing rancher, the volume is [an] informative... [and] historically valuable antidote to the TV cowboy".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/stan-steiner-3/the-ranchers-a-book-of-generations/|title=The Ranchers: A Book of Generations - By Stan Steiner|website=Kirkus Reviews|accessdate=May 25, 2018}}</ref>

Steiner died of a [[heart attack]] in 1987 inside his home in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa Fe]], [[New Mexico]]. He was 62 years old.<ref name="Dead"/> A collection of his essays was later put together in 1991 under the title ''The Waning of the West'', receiving acclaim from publications such as ''[[Publishers Weekly]]''. Writer [[John Nichols (novelist)|John Nichols]] composed the book's forward.<ref name="Waning">{{cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-312-03000-1|title=Nonfiction Book Review: ''The Waning of the West'' by Stan Steiner|website=[[Publishers Weekly]]|accessdate=May 25, 2018}}</ref>

==Viewpoints==
Several years after the historian's death, ''Publishers Weekly'' remarked,
{{Quote|Concerned with the varied ethnic groups that contributed to the spirit of individualism, freedom and expansiveness... of the area, Steiner... [wrote] about Anglos, Hispanics, Navajos and the Chinese, who built many of the railroads. With the decline of the family farm and the virtual abandonment of many small towns, he saw the spirit of the West fading, although he believed that the legend of the region might live on.<ref name="Waning"/>}}

Earlier in his life, Steiner had been a caustic critic of [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Richard Nixon]], arguing that the administration had sold out national interests in the West to private efforts by [[Corporation|corporations]].<ref name="Vanishing"/>

